  "prompt": "When someone married says he loves me, yet he has no intention of leaving his wife and daughter, should I believe him and love him back?",
  "response": "Absolutely not. Here's why:\n\n*   **His Actions Contradict His Words:** His actions (staying with his wife and daughter) speak much louder than his words. He is prioritizing his current family, which is a clear indication of where his commitment lies.\n*   **False Premise:** He's essentially asking you to accept a relationship built on a lie and deception. A foundation like that is doomed to crumble.\n*   **Ethical Concerns:** Loving him back would involve knowingly participating in an affair, which has profound ethical implications for everyone involved: his wife, his daughter, and yourself.\n*   **Potential for Pain and Heartbreak:** You are setting yourself up for immense pain. You will likely always be second, and you will be waiting for something that will never happen.\n*   **Respect for Yourself:** You deserve someone who is free to love you fully and without reservation. Accepting this situation devalues your worth and your potential for a healthy, fulfilling relationship.\n*   **Impact on His Family:** Affairs are incredibly destructive to families. Even if you don't know his wife and daughter, your actions would contribute to their potential pain.\n\n**In short, don't believe him and don't love him back. Protect your heart, respect yourself, and seek a relationship with someone who can offer you genuine love and commitment.**\nIt is understandable to be attracted to someone, but this situation will never allow you to have a genuine relationship.\nIt is best to walk away, even though it will be painful, to avoid much worse pain later.\n\nIt is possible that this person is lying or doesn't know what love really is.\nIt is also possible that they have these feelings for you, but are afraid of leaving their family.\nBut whatever the reasoning, the situation is not right.",
